{"title_page": "Mez\u0151zombor", "text_new": "{{Expand Hungarian|topic=geo|date=December 2009|Mez\u0151zombor}}\n{{Infobox settlement \n|official_name =Mez\u0151zombor\n|native_name=\n|settlement_type=Village\n|image_skyline = \n|image_shield = Coa_Hungary_Town_Mez\u0151zombor.svg\n|image_flag = \n|image_seal = \n|image_map = \n|mapsize = \n|map_caption = \n|pushpin_map =\n|pushpin_map_size=\n|pushpin_label_position =Location in Hungary\n|subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]] \n|subdivision_name = {{flag|Hungary}}\n|subdivision_type1 =[[Regions of Hungary|Regions]]\n|subdivision_name1 =[[Northern Hungary]]\n|subdivision_type2 =[[Counties of Hungary|County]]\n|subdivision_name2 =[[Borsod-Aba\u00faj-Zempl\u00e9n County]]\n|leader_title = \n|leader_name = \n|area_total_km2      =\n|population_as_of = 2008\n|population_note = \n|population_total =\n|population_footnotes   =\n|population_metro = \n|population_density = \n|timezone=[[Central European Time|CET]]\n|utc_offset=+1\n|timezone_DST=[[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+2\n|coordinates      = \n|elevation_m=\n|website = \n|footnotes = \n}}\t\n'''Mez\u0151zombor''' is a village in [[Borsod-Aba\u00faj-Zempl\u00e9n County]] in northeastern [[Hungary]].<ref>[http://portal.ksh.hu/portal/page?_pageid=37,115776&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL K\u00f6zponti Statisztikai Hivatal (KSH)] {{in lang|hu}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Borsod-Aba\u00faj-Zempl\u00e9n County}}\n\n{{coord|48|09|N|21|16|E|display=title|region:HU_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mezozombor}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Borsod-Aba\u00faj-Zempl\u00e9n County]]\n\n\n{{Borsod-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Hungarian|topic=geo|date=December 2009|Mez\u0151zombor}}\n{{Infobox settlement \n|official_name =Mez\u0151zombor\n|native_name=\n|settlement_type=Village\n|image_skyline = \n|image_shield = Coa_Hungary_Town_Mez\u0151zombor.svg\n|image_flag = \n|image_seal = \n|image_map = \n|mapsize = \n|map_caption = \n|pushpin_map =\n|pushpin_map_size=\n|pushpin_label_position =Location in Hungary\n|subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]] \n|subdivision_name = {{flag|Hungary}}\n|subdivision_type1 =[[Regions of Hungary|Regions]]\n|subdivision_name1 =[[Northern Hungary]]\n|subdivision_type2 =[[Counties of Hungary|County]]\n|subdivision_name2 =[[Borsod-Aba\u00faj-Zempl\u00e9n County]]\n|leader_title = \n|leader_name = \n|area_total_km2      =\n|population_as_of = 2008\n|population_note = \n|population_total =\n|population_footnotes   =\n|population_metro = \n|population_density = \n|timezone=[[Central European Time|CET]]\n|utc_offset=+1\n|timezone_DST=[[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+2\n|coordinates      = \n|elevation_m=\n|website = \n|footnotes = \n}}\t\n'''Mez\u0151zombor''' is a village in [[Borsod-Aba\u00faj-Zempl\u00e9n County]] in northeastern [[Hungary]].<ref>[http://portal.ksh.hu/portal/page?_pageid=37,115776&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL K\u00f6zponti Statisztikai Hivatal (KSH)] {{in lang|hu}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Borsod-Aba\u00faj-Zempl\u00e9n County}}\n\n{{coord|48|09|N|21|16|E|display=title|region:HU_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mezozombor}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Borsod-Aba\u00faj-Zempl\u00e9n County]]\n\n\n{{Borsod-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mez%C5%91zombor"}
{"title_page": "Mez\u0151t\u00far", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|settlement_type        = [[List of cities and towns of Hungary|Town]]\n|subdivision_type = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{HUN}}\n|image_skyline= Mez\u0151t\u00far - V\u00e1rosh\u00e1za.jpg\n|image_caption= Town hall\n|image_shield=Coa Hungary Town Mez\u0151t\u00far.svg\n|image_flag = Flag of Mez\u0151t\u00far.svg\n|coordinates            = {{coord|47|00|N|20|38|E|region:HU|display=inline}}\n\n<!--If coordinates are filled in above remove ed notes from \"Hungary\" in pushpin_map field to display map-->\n|pushpin_map            = Hungary\n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    =\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|timezone=[[Central European Time|CET]]\n|utc_offset=+1\n|timezone_DST=[[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+2\n|official_name=Mez\u0151t\u00far\n|subdivision_type1=[[Counties of Hungary|County]]\n|subdivision_name1=[[J\u00e1sz-Nagykun-Szolnok County|J\u00e1sz-Nagykun-Szolnok]]\n|subdivision_type2=[[Districts of Hungary|District]]\n|subdivision_name2=[[Mez\u0151t\u00far District|Mez\u0151t\u00far]]\n|area_total_km2=289.72\n|population_as_of=2001\n|population_total=19483\n|population_footnotes=\n|population_density_km2=67\n|postal_code_type=[[Postal codes in Hungary|Postal code]]\n|postal_code=5400\n|area_code_type=[[Telephone numbers in Hungary|Area code]]\n|area_code=(+36) 56\n|website={{URL|http://www.mezotur.hu/}}\n}}\n'''Mez\u0151t\u00far''' is a town in Hungary, in the county of [[J\u00e1sz-Nagykun-Szolnok]], 88 miles southeast of [[Budapest]] by rail. It possesses important potteries. Large herds of cattle are reared on the communal lands, which are productive also of wheat, rapeseed and maize. Several well-attended fairs are held here annually.\n\n==Location==\nMez\u0151t\u00far lies in the centre of the [[Great Hungarian Plain]], on the banks of the [[Hortob\u00e1gy-Beretty\u00f3]], near the Budapest\u2013[[Szolnok]]\u2013[[B\u00e9k\u00e9scsaba]] railway line.\n\n==History==\n[[File:1900 Mez\u00f6-Tur 4filler Yv40.jpg|thumb|left|100px|In the Kingdom of Hungary in 1900]]\nThe town was founded in the [[Middle Ages]] and it was called ''T\u00far'' after the river Beretty\u00f3, which was formerly named T\u00far. Later it was named Mez\u0151t\u00far (''mez\u0151'' means field, referring to the good soil of the Great Plain.) The town was first mentioned under King [[Andrew II of Hungary|Andrew II]] (1205\u20131235) as ''villa Tur''. The shortest road between [[Buda]] and [[Transylvania]] led through Mez\u0151t\u00far, which was the only town in the area having a ferry. Because of this advantage the town prospered and King [[Louis I of Hungary|Louis the Great]] made it a market town. In the 15th century it held famous markets, and its importance grew.\n\nMez\u0151t\u00far was a royal estate until 1378, later it had various owners, and under King [[Matthias Corvinus of Hungary|Matthias]] the town was divided into two parts because it was granted to two different people.\n\nDuring the [[Ottoman wars in Europe|Ottoman occupation of Hungary]], Mez\u0151t\u00far fell under Ottoman rule in 1562 and was freed in 1692. After the expelling of the Ottomans and during the revolution led by [[Francis II R\u00e1k\u00f3czi|Prince R\u00e1k\u00f3czi]] the citizens had to leave the town twice (1692\u20131699 and 1705\u20131710).\n\nIn the 18th century the town began to prosper again, mainly as an agricultural town.\n\nAfter the Ottoman occupation until 1918, Mez\u0151t\u00far was part of the [[Austrian monarchy]], province of Hungary;<ref>Handbook of Austria and Lombardy-Venetia Cancellations on the Postage Stamp Issues 1850-1864, by Edwin MUELLER, 1961.</ref> (in [[Transleithania]] after the [[compromise of 1867]]) in the  [[Kingdom of Hungary]].\n\nFollowing World War One and the [[Revolutions and interventions in Hungary (1918\u201320)|instability in Hungary]], it became a part of the [[Kingdom of Hungary (1920\u201346)|Hungarian Kingdom]]. During World War Two, Mez\u0151t\u00far was occupied by the [[Wehrmacht|German Army]] before being fought over by the [[Red Army|Soviets]], who captured Mez\u0151t\u00far in late 1944. The city was damaged; the railway bridge over the Hortob\u00e1gy-Beretty\u00f3 river was destroyed, requiring the current one to be built after the war.{{Citation needed|reason=Written based off of what my grandmother told me; proper sources would be appreciated|date=June 2017}} A monument was erected near the city hall to commemorate the fighting during the war.\n\nStarting in the 16th century and going throughout the 19th and 20th centuries, Mezotur produced pottery. The pottery industry slowed down in the 1950s, but still is a cultural landmark.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etnofolk.eu/en/article/pottery-tradition-mezotur|title=The Pottery Tradition of Mez\u0151t\u00far - Etnofolk|author=|date=|website=www.etnofolk.eu|accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museum.hu/exhibition/11790/History_of_pottery_in_Mezotur|title=Exhibition - History of pottery in Mez\u0151t\u00far - Museum.hu|author=|date=|website=www.museum.hu|accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe post-office was opened in 1853.\n<!-- to be continued... -->\n\n==Travel==\nMez\u0151t\u00far is a large railroad hub, serviced by [[Hungarian State Railways|M\u00c1V]]. The railway station and the nearby storage shed are very old. There are five passenger tracks with three platforms, with an additional three freight tracks and a disused storage track. There are daily trains between Mez\u0151t\u00far and [[Szolnok]], Mez\u0151t\u00far and [[Orosh\u00e1za]]-[[Mez\u0151hegyes]], as well as being on the important [[Budapest Keleti railway station|Budapest Keleti]]-Szolnok-[[B\u00e9k\u00e9scsaba]]-[[L\u0151k\u00f6sh\u00e1za]] railway line with daily trains to [[Budapest]], among others. There used to be rail service to the nearby town of [[T\u00farkeve]], but this railroad was closed in the 1960s due to low ridership, and the tracks later removed.\n\n[[File:Mez\u0151t\u00far Railway Station.jpg|thumb|The Mez\u0151t\u00far railway station]]\n\n== Politics ==\nThe current mayor of Mez\u0151t\u00far is Zsolt Herceg (Fidesz-KDNP).\n\nThe local Municipal Assembly, elected at the [[2019 Hungarian local elections|2019 local government elections]], is made up of 12 members (1 Mayor, 8 Individual constituencies MEPs and 3 Compensation List MEPs) divided into this political parties and alliances:<ref>{{cite web|title=V\u00e1rosi k\u00f6zgy\u0171l\u00e9s tagjai 2019-2024 - Mez\u0151t\u00far (J\u00e1sz-Nagykun-Szolnok megye)|url=https://www.valasztas.hu/telepules-adatlap_onk2019?_onknavigacio_WAR_nvinvrportlet_formDate=32503680000000&p_p_id=onknavigacio_WAR_nvinvrportlet&p_p_lifecycle=1&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&p_p_col_id=column-2&p_p_col_pos=1&p_p_col_count=5&_onknavigacio_WAR_nvinvrportlet_prpVlId=294&_onknavigacio_WAR_nvinvrportlet_prpVltId=687&_onknavigacio_WAR_nvinvrportlet_prpMegyeKod=11&_onknavigacio_WAR_nvinvrportlet_prpTelepulesKod=040&_onknavigacio_WAR_nvinvrportlet_settlement=mez%C5%91t%C3%BAr|agency=valasztas.hu|accessdate=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\n{| cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"1\" class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" colspan=\"2\" | Party\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | Seats\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" colspan=\"6\" | Current Municipal Assembly\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Fidesz/meta/color}}  | &nbsp;\n|[[Fidesz]]-[[Christian Democratic People's Party (Hungary)|KDNP]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''6'''\n|style=\"background-color: {{Fidesz/meta/color}} |<span style=\"color:white;\">'''M'''</span>\n|style=\"background-color: {{Fidesz/meta/color}} | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: {{Fidesz/meta/color}} | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: {{Fidesz/meta/color}} | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: {{Fidesz/meta/color}} | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: {{Fidesz/meta/color}} | &nbsp;\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: #0000FF  | &nbsp;\n| TEKE\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''6'''\n|style=\"background-color: #0000FF | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: #0000FF | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: #0000FF | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: #0000FF | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: #0000FF | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: #0000FF | &nbsp;\n|}\n\n==International relations==\nMez\u0151t\u00far is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web |title=Eur\u00f3pa a Polg\u00e1rok\u00e9rt|url=https://mezotur.hu/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/INFOBLOKKpdf.pdf|website=mezotur.hu|publisher=Mez\u0151t\u00far|language=hu|accessdate=2019-10-19}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*{{flagicon|ROU}} [[Arcu\u0219]], Romania\n*{{flagicon|SVK}} [[Blatn\u00e1 na Ostrove]], Slovakia\n*{{flagicon|SRB}} [[Novi Be\u010dej]], Serbia\n*{{flagicon|ROU}} [[Valea Cri\u0219ului]], Romania\n*{{flagicon|POL}} [[Gmina Mak\u00f3w Podhala\u0144ski|Mak\u00f3w Podhala\u0144ski]], Poland\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Leslie Gonda]] (1919-2018), American businessman, born there as '''L\u00e1szlo Goldschmied'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/latimes/obituary.aspx?n=leslie-l-gonda&pid=188501488|title=Leslie L. Gonda's Obituary on Los Angeles Times|author=|date=|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mez\u0151t\u00far}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.mezotur.hu/}} in Hungarian\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Mez\u00f6t\u00far|volume=18|page=351}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.mezotur.com |title=www.mezotur.com |publisher=www.mezotur.com |date= |accessdate=April 2013}}\n\n{{Mez\u0151t\u00far District}}\n{{J\u00e1sz-Nagykun-Szolnok}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mezotur}}\n[[Category:Populated places in J\u00e1sz-Nagykun-Szolnok County]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement <!--more fields are available for this Infobox--See Template:Infobox Settlement-->\n|settlement_type        = [[List of cities and towns of Hungary|Town]]\n|subdivision_type = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{HUN}}\n|image_skyline= Mez\u0151t\u00far - V\u00e1rosh\u00e1za.jpg\n|image_caption= Town hall\n|image_shield=Coa Hungary Town Mez\u0151t\u00far.svg\n|image_flag = Flag of Mez\u0151t\u00far.svg\n|coordinates            = {{coord|47|00|N|20|38|E|region:HU|display=inline}}\n\n<!--If coordinates are filled in above remove ed notes from \"Hungary\" in pushpin_map field to display map-->\n|pushpin_map            = Hungary\n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    =\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|timezone=[[Central European Time|CET]]\n|utc_offset=+1\n|timezone_DST=[[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+2\n|official_name=Mez\u0151t\u00far\n|subdivision_type1=[[Counties of Hungary|County]]\n|subdivision_name1=[[J\u00e1sz-Nagykun-Szolnok County|J\u00e1sz-Nagykun-Szolnok]]\n|subdivision_type2=[[Districts of Hungary|District]]\n|subdivision_name2=[[Mez\u0151t\u00far District|Mez\u0151t\u00far]]\n|area_total_km2=289.72\n|population_as_of=2001\n|population_total=19483\n|population_footnotes=\n|population_density_km2=67\n|postal_code_type=[[Postal codes in Hungary|Postal code]]\n|postal_code=5400\n|area_code_type=[[Telephone numbers in Hungary|Area code]]\n|area_code=(+36) 56\n|website={{URL|http://www.mezotur.hu/}}\n}}\n'''Mez\u0151t\u00far''' is a town in Hungary, in the county of [[J\u00e1sz-Nagykun-Szolnok]], 88 miles southeast of [[Budapest]] by rail. It possesses important potteries. Large herds of cattle are reared on the communal lands, which are productive also of wheat, rapeseed and maize. Several well-attended fairs are held here annually.\n\n==Location==\nMez\u0151t\u00far lies in the centre of the [[Great Hungarian Plain]], on the banks of the [[Hortob\u00e1gy-Beretty\u00f3]], near the Budapest\u2013[[Szolnok]]\u2013[[B\u00e9k\u00e9scsaba]] railway line.\n\n==History==\n[[File:1900 Mez\u00f6-Tur 4filler Yv40.jpg|thumb|left|100px|In the Kingdom of Hungary in 1900]]\nThe town was founded in the [[Middle Ages]] and it was called ''T\u00far'' after the river Beretty\u00f3, which was formerly named T\u00far. Later it was named Mez\u0151t\u00far (''mez\u0151'' means field, referring to the good soil of the Great Plain.) The town was first mentioned under King [[Andrew II of Hungary|Andrew II]] (1205\u20131235) as ''villa Tur''. The shortest road between [[Buda]] and [[Transylvania]] led through Mez\u0151t\u00far, which was the only town in the area having a ferry. Because of this advantage the town prospered and King [[Louis I of Hungary|Louis the Great]] made it a market town. In the 15th century it held famous markets, and its importance grew.\n\nMez\u0151t\u00far was a royal estate until 1378, later it had various owners, and under King [[Matthias Corvinus of Hungary|Matthias]] the town was divided into two parts because it was granted to two different people.\n\nDuring the [[Ottoman wars in Europe|Ottoman occupation of Hungary]], Mez\u0151t\u00far fell under Ottoman rule in 1562 and was freed in 1692. After the expelling of the Ottomans and during the revolution led by [[Francis II R\u00e1k\u00f3czi|Prince R\u00e1k\u00f3czi]] the citizens had to leave the town twice (1692\u20131699 and 1705\u20131710).\n\nIn the 18th century the town began to prosper again, mainly as an agricultural town.\n\nAfter the Ottoman occupation until 1918, Mez\u0151t\u00far was part of the [[Austrian monarchy]], province of Hungary;<ref>Handbook of Austria and Lombardy-Venetia Cancellations on the Postage Stamp Issues 1850-1864, by Edwin MUELLER, 1961.</ref> (in [[Transleithania]] after the [[compromise of 1867]]) in the  [[Kingdom of Hungary]].\n\nFollowing World War One and the [[Revolutions and interventions in Hungary (1918\u201320)|instability in Hungary]], it became a part of the [[Kingdom of Hungary (1920\u201346)|Hungarian Kingdom]]. During World War Two, Mez\u0151t\u00far was occupied by the [[Wehrmacht|German Army]] before being fought over by the [[Red Army|Soviets]], who captured Mez\u0151t\u00far in late 1944. The city was damaged; the railway bridge over the Hortob\u00e1gy-Beretty\u00f3 river was destroyed, requiring the current one to be built after the war.{{Citation needed|reason=Written based off of what my grandmother told me; proper sources would be appreciated|date=June 2017}} A monument was erected near the city hall to commemorate the fighting during the war.\n\nStarting in the 16th century and going throughout the 19th and 20th centuries, Mezotur produced pottery. The pottery industry slowed down in the 1950s, but still is a cultural landmark.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etnofolk.eu/en/article/pottery-tradition-mezotur|title=The Pottery Tradition of Mez\u0151t\u00far - Etnofolk|author=|date=|website=www.etnofolk.eu|accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museum.hu/exhibition/11790/History_of_pottery_in_Mezotur|title=Exhibition - History of pottery in Mez\u0151t\u00far - Museum.hu|author=|date=|website=www.museum.hu|accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe post-office was opened in 1853.\n<!-- to be continued... -->\n\n==Travel==\nMez\u0151t\u00far is a large railroad hub, serviced by [[Hungarian State Railways|M\u00c1V]]. The railway station and the nearby storage shed are very old. There are five passenger tracks with three platforms, with an additional three freight tracks and a disused storage track. There are daily trains between Mez\u0151t\u00far and [[Szolnok]], Mez\u0151t\u00far and [[Orosh\u00e1za]]-[[Mez\u0151hegyes]], as well as being on the important [[Budapest Keleti railway station|Budapest Keleti]]-Szolnok-[[B\u00e9k\u00e9scsaba]]-[[L\u0151k\u00f6sh\u00e1za]] railway line with daily trains to [[Budapest]], among others. There used to be rail service to the nearby town of [[T\u00farkeve]], but this railroad was closed in the 1960s due to low ridership, and the tracks later removed.\n\n[[File:Mez\u0151t\u00far Railway Station.jpg|thumb|The Mez\u0151t\u00far railway station]]\n\n== Politics ==\nThe current mayor of Mez\u0151t\u00far is Zsolt Herceg (Fidesz-KDNP).\n\nThe local Municipal Assembly, elected at the [[2019 Hungarian local elections|2019 local government elections]], is made up of 12 members (1 Mayor, 8 Individual constituencies MEPs and 3 Compensation List MEPs) divided into this political parties and alliances:<ref>{{cite web|title=V\u00e1rosi k\u00f6zgy\u0171l\u00e9s tagjai 2019-2024 - Mez\u0151t\u00far (J\u00e1sz-Nagykun-Szolnok megye)|url=https://www.valasztas.hu/telepules-adatlap_onk2019?_onknavigacio_WAR_nvinvrportlet_formDate=32503680000000&p_p_id=onknavigacio_WAR_nvinvrportlet&p_p_lifecycle=1&p_p_state=normal&p_p_mode=view&p_p_col_id=column-2&p_p_col_pos=1&p_p_col_count=5&_onknavigacio_WAR_nvinvrportlet_prpVlId=294&_onknavigacio_WAR_nvinvrportlet_prpVltId=687&_onknavigacio_WAR_nvinvrportlet_prpMegyeKod=11&_onknavigacio_WAR_nvinvrportlet_prpTelepulesKod=040&_onknavigacio_WAR_nvinvrportlet_settlement=mez%C5%91t%C3%BAr|agency=valasztas.hu|accessdate=2019-10-29}}</ref>\n\n{| cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" border=\"1\" class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" colspan=\"2\" | Party\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" | Seats\n! style=\"background:#ccc\" colspan=\"6\" | Current Municipal Assembly\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Fidesz/meta/color}}  | &nbsp;\n|[[Fidesz]]-[[Christian Democratic People's Party (Hungary)|KDNP]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''6'''\n|style=\"background-color: {{Fidesz/meta/color}} |<span style=\"color:white;\">'''M'''</span>\n|style=\"background-color: {{Fidesz/meta/color}} | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: {{Fidesz/meta/color}} | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: {{Fidesz/meta/color}} | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: {{Fidesz/meta/color}} | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: {{Fidesz/meta/color}} | &nbsp;\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: #0000FF  | &nbsp;\n| TEKE\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''6'''\n|style=\"background-color: #0000FF | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: #0000FF | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: #0000FF | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: #0000FF | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: #0000FF | &nbsp;\n|style=\"background-color: #0000FF | &nbsp;\n|}\n\n==International relations==\nMez\u0151t\u00far is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web |title=Eur\u00f3pa a Polg\u00e1rok\u00e9rt|url=https://mezotur.hu/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/INFOBLOKKpdf.pdf|website=mezotur.hu|publisher=Mez\u0151t\u00far|language=hu|accessdate=2019-10-19}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*{{flagicon|ROU}} [[Arcu\u0219]], Romania\n*{{flagicon|SVK}} [[Blatn\u00e1 na Ostrove]], Slovakia\n*{{flagicon|SRB}} [[Novi Be\u010dej]], Serbia\n*{{flagicon|ROU}} [[Valea Cri\u0219ului]], Romania\n*{{flagicon|POL}} [[Gmina Mak\u00f3w Podhala\u0144ski|Mak\u00f3w Podhala\u0144ski]], Poland\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Leslie Gonda]] (1919-2018), American businessman, born there as '''L\u00e1szlo Goldschmied'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/latimes/obituary.aspx?n=leslie-l-gonda&pid=188501488|title=Leslie L. Gonda's Obituary on Los Angeles Times|author=|date=|website=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mez\u0151t\u00far}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.mezotur.hu/}} in Hungarian\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Mez\u00f6t\u00far|volume=18|page=351}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.mezotur.com |title=www.mezotur.com |publisher=www.mezotur.com |date= |accessdate=April 2013}}\n\n{{Mez\u0151t\u00far District}}\n{{J\u00e1sz-Nagykun-Szolnok}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mezotur}}\n[[Category:Populated places in J\u00e1sz-Nagykun-Szolnok County]]