]]''\n|\"Solo\"\n|Season 1, episode 7\n|-\n|''[[Scorpion (TV series)|Scorpion]]''\n|\"Nude Kids on the Block\"\n|Season 4, episode 4\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|2018\n|''[[S.W.A.T. (2017 TV series)|S.W.A.T.]]''\n|\"Contamination\"\n|Season 1, episode 12\n|-\n|''Taken''\n|\"Strelochnik\"\n|Season 2, episode 8\n|-\n|''[[Insatiable (TV series)|Insatiable]]''\n|\"Banana Heart Banana\"\n|Season 1, episode 10\n|-\n|''[[All American (TV series)|All American]]''\n|\"Lose Yourself\"\n|Season 1, episode 4\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2019\n|''[[Chicago Med]]''\n|\"Old Flames, New Sparks\"\n|Season 4, episode 16\n|-\n|''[[Proven Innocent]]''\n|\"A Minor Confession\"\n|Season 1, episode 3\n|-\n|''[[Dynasty (2017 TV series)|Dynasty]]''\n|\"New Lady in Town\"\n|Season 2, episode 20\n|-\n|''[[Grand Hotel (TV series)|Grand Hotel]]''\n|\"Groom Service\"\n|Season 1, episode 9\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2020\n|''[[FBI: Most Wanted]]''\n|\"Invisible\"\n|Season 1, episode 7\n|-\n|''Chicago Med''\n|\"It May Not Be Forever\"\n|Season 5, episode 14\n|-\n|''FBI: Most Wanted''\n|\"Predators\"\n|Season 1, episode 8\n|-\n|''Dynasty''\n|\"You Make Being a Priest Sound Like Something Bad\"\n|Season 3, episode 18\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0444709}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Keene, Elodie}}\n[[Category:American television directors]]\n[[Category:Television producers from California]]\n[[Category:Women television producers]]\n[[Category:Film directors from California]]\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American women film directors]]\n[[Category:Women television directors]]\n[[Category:People from Paso Robles, California]]\n[[Category:Haas family]]\n[[Category:American people of Acadian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name                      = Elodie Keene\n| image                     = \n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = \n| othername                 =\n| birth_date                = {{birth date and age|1949|04|10}}\n| birth_place               = [[Berkeley, California]], U.S.\n| death_date                = \n| death_place               = \n| alma_mater                = \n| occupation                = Film director, television director, television editor, television producer\n| years_active              = 1979\u2013present\n| spouse                    = [[imdbname:0287416|Bruce Fortune]]<br>(?\u2013present; 2 children)\n| parents                   = Yvonne Cyr Keene Koshland <br> Jim Keene\n| family                    = [[Christopher Keene]] (brother)<br>[[Daniel E. Koshland Jr.]] (stepfather)\n}}\n\n'''Elodie Keene''' (born April 10, 1949 in [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]], [[California]]) is an American film/television director, producer and editor. As a television director her credits include ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'', ''[[NYPD Blue]]'', ''[[The Practice]]'', ''[[Ally McBeal]]'', ''[[Charmed]]'', ''[[Felicity (TV series)|Felicity]]'', ''[[The Wire]]'', ''[[House (TV series)|House, M.D.]]'', ''[[The Closer]]'', ''[[Nip/Tuck]]'' and among other series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/84/Elodie-Keene.html |title=Elodie Keene Biography (1948-) |publisher=Film Reference |accessdate=September 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\nShe has won three [[Primetime Emmy Awards]], two for best dramatic series and one for best editing in a single camera series, all for her work on ''[[L.A. Law]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/award_history_search?person=+Elodie+Keene&program=&start_year=1949&end_year=2010&network=All&web_category=All&winner=All |title=Elodie Keene Primetime Emmy Award wins and nominations |publisher=Primetime Emmy\u00ae Award Database |accessdate=September 27, 2011}}</ref> Elodie Keene is the daughter of Yvonne (n\u00e9e Cyr) and Jim Keene.<ref>{{Cite web|first= |last= |authorlink= |title= Daniel Koshland, Jr. Retrospective Oral History Project: Yvonne Koshland - Interviews conducted by Sally Smith Hughes in 2011|publisher=[[University of California - Berkeley]] Regional Oral History Office - The Bancroft Library |date= 2014|url=http://digitalassets.lib.berkeley.edu/roho/ucb/text/koshland_yvonne_2014.pdf  |accessdate=}}</ref> Her mother was of [[Acadians|Acadian]], [[German Americans|German]], and [[Scottish Americans|Scottish]] descent.<ref>Smith, p. 1</ref> Her parents divorced in 1953 and her mother remarried to Jim San Jule in 1954 until their divorce in 1970.<ref>Smith, p. 6</ref><ref>{{Cite web|first=Dave |last=Weinstein |authorlink=   |title=Jim San Jule: Tireless Crusader   |publisher=Eichler Network|date= |url=https://www.eichlernetwork.com/article/jim-san-jule-tireless-crusader?page=0,0  |accessdate=April 5, 2019}}</ref> She has three siblings: Philip Keene (born 1941), [[Christopher Keene]] (born 1946),<ref>Smith, p. 5</ref> and Tamsen (n\u00e9e San Jule) Calhoon (born 1956).<ref>Smith, p. 6</ref> Her mother remarried to biochemist [[Daniel E. Koshland Jr.]] in 2000, of the Haas family, the owners of [[Levi Strauss & Co]].\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Director===\n\n{|class=wikitable style=font-size:90%:background:#f9f9f9 border=2 cellpadding=4\n|- align=center\n! style=background:#B0C4DE | Year\n! style=background:#B0C4DE | Film\n! style=background:#B0C4DE | Episode Title\n! style=background:#B0C4DE | Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1990\n|rowspan=18|''[[L.A. Law]]''\n|\"The Bitch Is Back\"\n|Season 5, episode 1\n|-\n|\"Forgive Me Father, for I Have Sued\"\n|Season 4, episode 20\n|-\n|rowspan=4|1991\n|\"TV or Not TV\"\n|Season 6, episode 2\n|-\n|\"There Goes the Judge\"\n|Season 5, episode 20\n|-\n|\"He's a Crowd\"\n|Season 5, episode 12\n|-\n|\"Splatoon\"\n|Season 5, episode 9\n|-\n|rowspan=5|1992\n|\"Second Time Around\"\n|Season 7, episode 2\n|-\n|\"Silence of the Lambskins\"\n|Season 6, episode 1